}}The '''Washington Park Court District''' is a [[Grand Boulevard, Chicago|Grand Boulevard]] [[Community areas of Chicago|community area]] neighborhood on the [[South Side (Chicago)|South Side]] of [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]].  It was designated a [[Chicago Landmark]] on October 2, 1991.<ref name=CL>{{cite web|url=http://www.cityofchicago.org/Landmarks/W/WashingtonPark.html|accessdate=2007-03-30|date=2003|publisher=City of Chicago Department of Planning and Development, Landmarks Division|title=Washington Park Court District}}</ref>  Despite its name, it is not located within either the [[Washington Park, Chicago (neighborhood)|Washington Park]] community area or the [[Washington Park (Chicago park)|Washington Park]] park, but is one block north of both. The district was named for the Park.<ref name=SCRS/>

The district includes [[row house]]s built between 1895 and 1905, with addresses of 4900&ndash;4959 South Washington Park Court and 417&ndash;439 East 50th Street.<ref name=CL/>  Many of the houses share architectural features.<ref name=AGtC/>  The neighborhood was part of the early twentieth century [[segregation]]ist racial [[covenant]] wave that swept Chicago following the [[Great Migration]].<ref name=PTI/>  The community area has continued to be almost exclusively African American since the 1930s.<ref name=GB/>

==Architecture==
