Washington Park Court, which runs [[One-way traffic|one-way]] northbound from East 50th Street to East 49th Street, is a one-[[city block]]-long street located at 432 east in the Chicago street numbering system. Officially, it runs from 4900 south to 5060 south in the numbering system.<ref name=SCRS/> The street and several adjacent homes at one end are recognized as a distinct district within the city, according to the City of Chicago Department of Planning and Development.<ref name=CL/> In May 1990, the district was one of ten that were under consideration for Chicago Landmark status,<ref name=Tcsatfls/> and it was designated a Chicago Landmark on October 2, 1991.<ref name=CL/>  The district was named for the Park,<ref name=SCRS/> which was designed by [[landscape architecture|landscape architect]] [[Frederick Law Olmsted]].<ref name=WPP>{{cite web|url=http://www.encyclopedia.chicagohistory.org/pages/1319.html|author=Bachin, Robin|title=Washington Park (Park)|work=The Encyclopedia of Chicago|publisher=[[Chicago Historical Society]]|date=2005|accessdate=2009-02-14}}</ref>

The T. G. Dickinson Real Estate Company, which created the subdivision in 1892, mandated {{convert|10|ft|m|adj=on}} [[Setback (architecture)|setback]]s for all properties and originally sold lots in small groups of two or three.<ref name=AGtC/>  Between 1895 and 1905, the tone of the district became clear with the development of its [[row house]]s.<ref name=CL/><ref name=AGtC/> In 1990, the district contained forty-nine row houses that span a wide variety of architectural styles including [[Classical Revival]] and [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque]].<ref name=Tcsatfls>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CSTB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EB372E4A4B86E58&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Ten city sites are targeted for landmark status|accessdate=2009-01-02|date=1990-05-11|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Busk, Celeste}}</ref>  As of 2004, the district contained fifty-one properties.<ref name=AGtC>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=aQE21zTaju8C&pg=PA415&dq=%22Washington+Park+Court%22&client=firefox-a|title=AIA Guide to Chicago|edition=2nd|pages=428|editor=Sinkevitch, Alice|chapter=Oakland/Kenwood: Washington Park Court: S. Washington Park Ct. from 49th to 50th Sts.|publisher=Harcourt, Inc.|isbn=0-15-602908-1|year=2004|accessdate=2008-01-04|page=415}}</ref>  The street hosts residential designs of architect [[Henry Newhouse]] and of developers Andrew and John Dubach.<ref name=CL/>  At least twenty-five of the lots were developed by the Dubaches and at least twelve of the properties were designed by Newhouse.<ref name=AGtC/>  Their architectural contributions set the tone for the block, which uses mostly [[brick]] and [[limestone]] houses that share [[porch]] and [[cornice]] lines.<ref name=AGtC/>  Most houses have [[mansard roof|mansard]]s or recessed roofs with [[bay window|bay]] fronts.<ref name=AGtC/>

==Demographic change==
Between 1900 and 1934 the African American population in Chicago grew from 30,000 to 236,000.<ref name=THBHvL/>  The population was initially diluted in scattered places, but during this time, due to the change in the [[Demographics of Chicago|demographics of Chicago]], it became concentrated in two large strips of land.<ref name=THBHvL/>  The racial concentration was enforced by violence for few decades, until restrictive covenants became the preferred way to enforce [[segregation]].<ref name=THBHvL>{{cite journal|url=http://lawreview.law.ucdavis.edu/issues/Vol20/Issue3/DavisVol20No3_Kamp.pdf|title=The History Behind Hansberry v. Lee|accessdate=2009-01-02|publisher=University of California, Davis|work=UC Davis Law Review|volume=20|pages=481-500|author=Kamp, Allen R.|year=1986&ndash;1987}}</ref> Although they were previously rare, racially restrictive [[covenant]]s among property owners that outlawed the purchase, lease, or occupation of their properties by African Americans became common in Chicago in the 1920s following the [[Great Migration]],<ref name=RC>{{cite web|url=http://www.encyclopedia.chicagohistory.org/pages/1067.html|title=Restrictive Covenants|accessdate=2008-12-31|year=2005|publisher=[[Chicago Historical Society]]||work=The Electronic Encyclopedia of Chicago|author=Hirsch, Arnold R.}}</ref> especially after the 1926 [[United States Supreme Court]] upheld racially restrictive covenants in Corrigan v. Buckley ({{ussc|271|323|1926}}).<ref name=THBHvL>{{cite journal|url=http://lawreview.law.ucdavis.edu/issues/Vol20/Issue3/DavisVol20No3_Kamp.pdf|title=The History Behind Hansberry v. Lee|accessdate=2009-01-02|publisher=University of California, Davis|work=UC Davis Law Review|volume=20|pages=481&ndash;500|author=Kamp, Allen R.|year=1986&ndash;1987}}</ref><ref name=RC/>

During the first half of the 20th Century, [[Black Belt (region of Chicago)|The Black Belt]] was the term for the African American neighborhood from 22nd Street to 31st Street along [[State Street (Chicago)|State Street]] on Chicago's South Side.<ref name=BB/>  South Side local businessmen and the [[University of Chicago]] became alarmed at the prospect of poorer blacks moving from the Black Belt due to a combination of racial succession and economic decline.<ref name=W>{{cite web|url=http://www.encyclopedia.chicagohistory.org/pages/1378.html|title=Woodlawn|accessdate=2008-12-31|year=2005|publisher=[[Chicago Historical Society]]||work=The Electronic Encyclopedia of Chicago|author=Seligman, Amanda}}</ref>  Because 85% of Chicago was covenanted, most black neighborhoods were bounded by covenanted areas.<ref name=THBHvL/>  The Washington Park Court Improvement Association changed its focus from neighborhood improvement projects, such as planting shrubs and cleaning streets, to upholding segregationist policies.<ref name=PTI>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=vPLEXRfnzJAC&pg=PA140&dq=%22Washington+Park+Court%22&client=firefox-a|title=Packing Them In: An Archaeology of Environmental Racism in Chicago, 1865&ndash;1954|chapter=Planning and Environmental Inequality|accessdate=2009-01-03|year=2005|publisher=Lexington Books|author=Washington, Sylvia Hood|isbn=0739110292}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=VH0SFTzWdokC&pg=PA624&dq=%22Washington+Park+Court%22&client=firefox-a|title=An American Dilemma: The Negro Problem and Modern Democracy, Vol. 2|accessdate=2008-01-04|year=1996|publisher=Transaction Publishers|isbn=9781560008576|author=Myrdal, Gunnar and Sissela Bok}}</ref>  When necessary, the organization resorted to violence to pursue its segregationist purpose, and between 1917 and 1921, bombs were used to discourage encroachment into majority white neighborhoods.  The bombs were used at the residences of African Americans as well as the properties of real estate agents and bankers.<ref name=PTI/>

Eventually the term Black Belt included the region from 39th Street to 95th Street between the [[Dan Ryan Expressway]] and [[Lake Michigan]].<ref name=BB>{{cite web|url=http://www.encyclopedia.chicagohistory.org/pages/140.html|title=Black Belt|accessdate=2009-02-14|year=2005|publisher=[[Chicago Historical Society]]||work=The Electronic Encyclopedia of Chicago|author=Best, Wallace}}</ref> Since the [[1930 United States Census]], the Grand Boulevard community area has been over 90% African American.  In both the [[1960 United States Census|1960]] and [[1990 United States Census|1990 Census]], the community area was over 99% African American.  As of the [[2000 United States Census|2000 Census]], the area was 98.2% African American and 0.8% Hispanic.<ref name=GB>{{cite web|url=http://www.encyclopedia.chicagohistory.org/pages/537.html|title=Grand Boulevard|accessdate=2009-02-14|year=2005|publisher=[[Chicago Historical Society]]||work=The Electronic Encyclopedia of Chicago|author=Best, Wallace}}</ref>

